@Bill
I was a tad worried about the "A or E" situation, not knowing either the key or the guy. But since the guy's name was French, I figured ARISTIDE was more likely than Aristida.

That's the key to solving crosswords, in my opinion: you don't need to know everything, you just need to know enough to make an educated guess.

@Bill 

Jean-Bertrand Aristide is well worth looking up.

So much about what has gone on in Haiti is permanently hidden, but I suspect that there was a conflict between the effort to pull Haiti out of chaos and poverty and the wishes of corporations and the government of the United States. Not, unfortunately, a new story.

@The X-Phile
I read SONATA THING as "So 'not a thing'," like "So yesterday!", which doesn't make perfect sense, but made me smile.

My discomfort with FORZA MOMENT was different--although I've certainly seen markings like "con tutta la forza" ("with all possible force"), I'm more used to "sforzando" or just "forte." "Forza," all by itself, would almost never occur.

@The X-Phile

Seems you and I pronounce "sonata" differently (suh·naa·tuh according one internet source, and the way I pronounce it).  So to me, I would choose "[It']s not a thing" as the correct interpretation.

But since I got all the answers, I did not spend a lot of time analyzing  why there was something wrong with them, as some have done.  Some take sport in nitpicking the puzzle, I take sport in nitpicking the nitpickers.

